holy [is He] forever and for all eternity.” The Talmud, ({\highlight7 <IT>}Maseches Chulin{\highlight7 <ITC>} 91b) refers to this verse 
as the “Sanctification of the Angels.” According to {\highlight7 <IT>}Avudraham{\highlight7 <ITC>} and {\highlight7 <IT>}Yaavetz,{\highlight7 <ITC>} this {\highlight7 <IT>}Kedushah{\highlight7 <ITC>} has 
been inserted here to refute those who maintain that God relinquished His control over the 
heavenly bodies, and they are now able to function independently. We are therefore told that all 
the heavenly hosts proclaim God’s sanctification and dominion over all the universe.{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*42>}42{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <IT>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Ofanim, Chayos haKodash,{\highlight7 <ITC>} and {\highlight7 <IT>}Serafim{\highlight7 <ITC>} are various classes of Angels. Ofanim denotes 
animated wheels as conceived in association with the Heavenly throne. (Avudraham); {\highlight7 <IT>}Chayos{\highlight7 <ITC>} 
are those angels who exist eternally (Yaavetz; some angels exist only for short times for specific 
functions.) {\highlight7 <IT>}Serafim{\highlight7 <ITC>} indicate “beings of fire.”{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*43>}43{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <IT>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Ezekiel{\highlight7 <ITC>} 3:12. According to the {\highlight7 <IT>}Kuzari,{\highlight7 <ITC>} God’s glory is a euphemism for God Himself. Thus 
