dividends. {\highlight7 <IT>}Midrash Rabba, Deuteronomy 3:6{\highlight7 <ITC>}{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*46>}46{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Since the blessing began with the praise of God as the Former of light Who continually 
renews the creation, it concludes on the same note.{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*47>}47{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <IT>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Psalms{\highlight7 <ITC>} 136:7.{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*48>}48{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}We pray that we will be worthy of enjoying the original light of creation, which God put 
aside for the righteous in the future world.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Yaavetz{\highlight7 <ITC>}{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*49>}49{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}When reciting this blessing, bear in mind that even though the heavenly spheres appear 
immense to us and we attach much importance to them because of the vital functions they 
perform, in the eyes of their Creator they are no greater than worms. On the contrary, His 
wisdom and providence are more acutely recognized in an ant or bee because, in spite of their 
minuteness, they are endowed with a complex of faculties and organs.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Kuzari{\highlight7 <ITC>}{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*50>}50{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}The {\highlight7 <IT>}Kuzari{\highlight7 <ITC>} writes, “When reciting the blessing ‘Unbounded Love’ {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e0\'c7\'e4\'c2\'e1\'c8\'e4 \'f8\'c7\'e1\'cc\'c8\'e4{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch , one should 
bear in mind that God’s Divine influence is especially directed at the Jewish People who receive 
it as naturally as a mirror receives rays of light. He should also bear in mind that the Torah is the 
expression of God’s will and through it He establishes His dominion on earth as in heaven. 
Whenever an individual or a community attains a high degree of spiritual purity, they become 
worthy of receiving the Divine light to guide their destiny in a miraculous manner far removed 
from the ordinary course of events which affect the world. This special relationship with the 
Creator is called love.{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*51>}51{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}God bestowed His great and abundant pity on us after we sinned in making the golden 
calf. He not only pardoned us, but gave us the Second Tablets and ordained the construction of 
the Tabernacle ({\highlight7 <IT>}Mishkan{\highlight7 <ITC>}) for His Divine Presence to dwell among us.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Siach Yitzchok{\highlight7 <ITC>}{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*52>}52{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}We {\highlight7 <IT>}preserve{\highlight7 <ITC>} the Torah by not forgetting its teachings; we {\highlight7 <IT>}practice{\highlight7 <ITC>} the commandments and 
we {\highlight7 <IT>}fulfill{\highlight7 <ITC>} them by making them permanent parts of our lives.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Siach Yitzchok{\highlight7 <ITC>}{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*53>}53{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Make us singlehearted and undivided in our love and reverence of Your Name. Keep us 
from distraction of personal thoughts and selfish motives.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Siach Yitzchok{\highlight7 <ITC>}{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*54>}54{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}When one has to receive a favor that is completely undeserved, he feels a sense of shame. 
We therefore pray to God, that our redemption will not be “handed out” to us without merit 
and cause us to be ashamed. We proclaim that since we “trusted in His Name” and accepted the 
bitterness of our exile our deliverance is not totally undeserved.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Siach Yitzchok{\highlight7 <ITC>}{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*55>}55{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}May we return from our exile with our heads held high, not in meekness.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Siach Yitzchok{\highlight7 <ITC>}{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*56>}56{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Even if we do not deserve to be saved in our own merit, save us anyhow because You 
perform acts of deliverance.{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*57>}57{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}At the moment God gave the Torah to the Jews at Sinai, we became His chosen people and 
were brought close to Him for eternity.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Siach Yitzchok{\highlight7 <ITC>}{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*58>}58{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}These final words complete the prayer begun earlier: “Bring us in peace, and lead us 
upright to our land, so that we may give thanks to You, and proclaim Your Oneness, with 
love.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Siach Yitzchok{\highlight7 <ITC>} {\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*59>}59{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <IT>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Deuteronomy{\highlight7 <ITC>} 6:4. It is customary to recite this verse aloud, the ear hearing what the lips 
utter. This helps one concentrate on the meaning of this important declaration. Interestingly, 
the last letter of the first word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'f9\'d1\'c0\'ee\'c7\'f2{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  and last letter of {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e0\'c6\'e7\'c8\'e3{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  are written larger than the others. These 
two letters form the word {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch r\'c5\'e3{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch “witness”Ði.e., every Jew by saying Shema testifies to God’s 
unity.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Avudraham{\highlight7 <ITC>}{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}Customarily one closes his eyes when pronouncing this testimony in order to shut out all 
distractions, and to concentrate all one’s thought on God’s unity. The last word, {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e0\'c6\'e7\'c8\'e3{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  “One,” is 
to be said with special emphasis, drawing it out for the length of time needed to reflect that God, 
the Giver and Sustainer of life Whose Providence guides the destinies of all men, is the unique 
God of Israel, that He is alone in His world, ruling all four corners of the universe.{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*60>}60{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Jacob wished to reveal to his sons the ‘end of the days,’ whereupon the Shechinah 
departed from him. Said he, “Perhaps, Heaven forbid! there is one unfit among my children.” 
His sons exclaimed to him, “Hear Israel” etc., just as there is only One in your heart so is there 
only One in our heart. Ben Lakish explained that Jacob said “Blessed [is His] Name” in response 
to his sons’ exclamation. The Sages wondered, “Shall we recite it aloud when our teacher Moses 
did not say it? Shall we not say it at all, when Jacob ordained it?” Thus the Rabbis enacted that it 
be said quietly.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Maseches Pesachim{\highlight7 <ITC>} 56a.{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}When Moses went up to the heavens, he heard the angels praise God by saying, “Blessed [is 
His] Name, etc.” When he returned to earth, he taught it to the Jewish People. We say it in an 
undertone so as not to offend the angels. On Yom Kippur however, when we are considered like 
angels, we are permitted to say {\highlight7 @hh}{\highlight7 <HEB>}\rtlch \'e1\'cc\'c8\'f8\'e5\'cc\'ea\'c0 \'f9\'d1\'c5\'ed{\highlight7 {\ltrch @ee}}{\highlight7 {\ltrch<}{\ltrch ENG}{\ltrch>}}\ltrch  aloud.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Midrash Rabba{\highlight7 <ITC>} to {\highlight7 <IT>}Deuteronomy{\highlight7 <ITC>}{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*61>}61{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Our Sages ({\highlight7 <IT>}Sifrei{\highlight7 @b2} to Deuteronomy 31) explain “With all your heart” to mean “With all 
your desiresÐincluding the evil inclination,” i.e., subject your earthly passions and ambitions 
to God’s Law and make them instruments for His service.{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*62>}62{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}The Sages (ibid.) take these words to mean “With your whole lifeÐeven to the last drop of 
blood.” It was such an understanding that led Rabbi Akiva to say, when the executioner was 
tearing his flesh with iron hooks, “All my life, I have longed for this moment. I have loved God 
with all my heart and with all my might; and now at last, I can love Him with my whole life.” It 
was this concept that gave Jewish martyrs the courage to lay down their lives for their faith.{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*63>}63{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}The Sages ({\highlight7 <IT>}ibid.{\highlight7 <ITC>}) explain, “With whatever lot Providence has assigned to you,” i.e., despite 
whatever material sacrifice your loyalty to God and to Torah might entail.{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*64>}64{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}The teachings of the Torah should be ever fresh in your minds, as though you received it 
{\highlight7 <IT>}today.{\highlight7 <ITC>}Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Ibid.{\highlight7 <ITC>}{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*65>}65{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}See to it that your children have a clear, and not a confused, stammering knowledge of the 
Torah.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Ibid.{\highlight7 <ITC>}{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*66>}66{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <IT>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Deuteronomy{\highlight7 <ITC>} 6:5±9. This paragraph contains 10 commandments: 1) accepting the “yoke” 
of heaven; 2) proclaiming the Unity of God; 3) loving God; 4) studying Torah (and you shall 
speak of them); 5) teaching your children; 6±7) reciting Shema in the evening and in the 
morning; 8±9) putting on the {\highlight7 <IT>}tefillin{\highlight7 <ITC>} of the hand and head; 10) putting up {\highlight7 <IT>}mezuzos{\highlight7 <ITC>} on the door 
posts.{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*67>}67{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}The service of the heart is prayer, as David said ({\highlight7 <IT>}Psalms{\highlight7 <ITC>} 141:2) “May my prayers be 
acceptable to You as an incense [service].” {\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*68>}68{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}God will make it rain at night so as not to cause you discomfort.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Rashi{\highlight7 <ITC>}{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*69>}69{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Reward and punishment are here connected with the rainfalls vital to the Land of Israel. 
The heavy rains which open the growing season in the fall and the showers which fall while the 
grain is ripening are of utmost importance.{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*70>}70{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}One who is satisfied can easily be induced to forget the Source of his fullness.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Rashi{\highlight7 <ITC>}{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*71>}71{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}No extension will be given. The “generation of the flood” was granted a reprieve of 120 
years (Genesis 6:3) because they did not have from whom to learn; but you do have from whom 
to learn.{\highlight7 <IT>}ÐSifrei{\highlight7 @b2}, cited by {\highlight7 <IT>}Rashi{\highlight7 <ITC>}{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*72>}72{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Even in exile you must fulfill God’s commandmentsÐSifrei cited by {\highlight7 <IT>}Rashi{\highlight7 <ITC>}{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*73>}73{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Between your eyes is not to be taken literally. The correct position of the phylactery of the 
head ({\highlight7 <IT>}shel rosh{\highlight7 <ITC>}) is at the edge of the hair line directly above the place which is between the eyes.{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*74>}74{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}From the moment your son knows how to talk, begin teaching him the Torah.Ð{\highlight7 <IT>}Rashi.{\highlight7 <ITC>}{\highlight7 <QL>}\par
{\highlight7 @b1}{\highlight7 <EM>}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ6>}{\highlight7 <SUP2.5>}{\highlight7 <*75>}75{\highlight7 @b2}{\highlight7 <EN>}{\highlight7 <SZ9>}{\highlight7 <SUP0>}Rabbi Yehuda bar Chaviva said that this third section was added to {\highlight7 <IT>}Sh’ma{\highlight7 <ITC>} because of six 
